ont-size:12pt">. We believe other organisations such as the Minerals Producers Association</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (MPA)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and CBI Minerals Group are best placed to comment in other areas.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Qu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">estion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">  What is the contribution to the UK economy of extractive industries in the UK?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is important at the outset to recognise the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">role</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and impact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that terrestrial planning policy has on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">marine minerals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This is particularly true in areas where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">land </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">based</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> minerals are under local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">planning pressures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which restricts supply</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> allowing m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arine minerals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a greater market share.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is therefore very important to e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nsu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that terrestrial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">planning policy specifically references consideration of marine </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">minerals as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> way of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> maximising the potential of this indigenous resource.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hilst minerals guidance is set out under the National Planning Policy Framework, with local aggregates assessments undertaken by Local Authorities, consideration of other sources, such as marin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e minerals (which are outside of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">spatial demarcation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of a Local Authority)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is needed as part of broader supply chain considerations. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lear policy guidance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ensuring </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">marine minerals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> contribution continues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the context of UK supply of minerals, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> maximise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the overall</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> benefit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the UK economy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A robust regulatory regime exists</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for marine aggregates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, which is managed through the Marin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Management Organisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(MMO) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(England)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Natural Resources Wales (Wales)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> There is currently no extraction in Scottish or Northern Irish waters.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Operating businesses in this sector have a significant capital asset base to maintain, requiring security of mineral reserves</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and it is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">important that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Marine Licence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">application p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rocedure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recognises the long term nature </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and scale </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the associated investment profile</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> without </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">introducing an excessive burden on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Crown Estate has introduced a procedure designed to optimise the use of the seabed whilst working within </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the guidelines introduced by the marine planning process that is currently being developed by the MMO. This procedure is also designed to provide a safeguarding protocol for key resources.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MPA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recently commissioned </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a study</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to assess the contribution the mineral products sector (pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">incipally minerals extracted to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> supply the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">construction sector) makes to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK economy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and would be able to provide conclusions outlining the Gross Value Added (GVA) contribution the sector makes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to the UK economy.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Alongside the economic contribution minerals production makes to the UK, it is also important to recognise the need for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">secure supply</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of minerals for the construction industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Millions of tons of marine sand and gravel are used across the construction industry and for coastal management and land reclamation each year. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Crown Estate licens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es nearly all marine seabed sand and gravel resourc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es lying offshore around the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">been licensing the activity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">over 50 years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Extraction of about 20 million tonnes p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">er </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nnum</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of marine aggregates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">occurs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">off the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> coast of England and Wales.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As set out in the Marine Policy Statement</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for the UK, m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arine mineral from UK seabed is v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iew</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed as a world class resource.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It is an important source for security of supply and there is always the potential opportunity to export our dredged materials to other countries in Europe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As we adapt to cl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">imate change, large volumes of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">marine sand and grave</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ls are used in beach replenishment schemes. Aggregates are pumped directly from dredgers onto beaches,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> providing coastal protection, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nhancing the amenity value and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">providing security to the local economy, for example on the coast of Lincolnshire.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In addit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ion, marine sands are used in land reclamation schemes, infilli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng areas in ports and harbours </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to reclaim land from the sea. Recent examples of reclamation include the runway extension at Ronaldsway airport on The Isle of Man and the London Gateway port dev</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">elopment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is important to note here that sourcing of marine based minerals ensure that the schemes undertaken are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">economically viable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and it is likely that without these vital resource</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> this would not be the case. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Marine sourced mineral is unique in te</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rms of the ability to import and place large quantities of mineral in a short space of time without the need for importation by road.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Crown Estate is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">responsible for leasing extraction of minerals lying below the UK sea bed, including deposits of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> potash.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Potash is a generic term for a variety of potassium bearing minerals; in part</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">icular it is Sylvinite that is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> currently</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mined in the UK. Around 90 per cent of UK potash is used in the production of fertiliser with the remainder being used in the che</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and pharmaceutical industries. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Approximately 60 per cent of all UK production is exported each year.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:2pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Boulby potash mine, situated on the North Yorkshire coast, is the UK's only commercial potash mine and the most important non-hydrocarbon minera</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l operation in Britain. The mine, which started production in 1973 and is currently managed by Cleveland Potash Ltd, employs </span><span style="font-family:Calibr